                    "title": "Form ～ます",
                    "short_description": "Polite present tense form",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～ます — Polite Present/Future Tense\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～ます` is the **polite verb form** for present and future tense. It's the standard form for conversations with strangers, coworkers, teachers, or anyone you want to show respect to.\n\n> ⚠️ Japanese has no separate future tense — context tells you whether the action is happening now or later.\n\n---\n\n### Formation rules\n\n| Group | Dictionary Form | ～ます Form |\n|-------|----------------|-----------|\n| Group 1 (u-verbs) | 書く | `書きます` |\n| | 飲む | `飲みます` |\n| | 話す | `話します` |\n| | 買う | `買います` |\n| Group 2 (ru-verbs) | 食べる | `食べます` |\n| | 見る | `見ます` |\n| Group 3 (irregular) | する | `します` |\n| | くる | `来ます` |\n\n**Group 1:** shift the final u-row sound to i-row, add `ます`.\n**Group 2:** drop る, add `ます`.\n\n---\n\n### Conjugation table (食べる)\n\n| Form | Japanese | Meaning |\n|------|----------|---------|\n| Present/Future (+) | `食べます` | eat / will eat |\n| Negative | `食べません` | don't eat |\n| Past (+) | `食べました` | ate |\n| Past (-) | `食べませんでした` | didn't eat |\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n毎朝コーヒーを飲みます。\nI drink coffee every morning.\n```\n\n```\n明日東京へ行きます。\nI'm going to Tokyo tomorrow.\n```\n\n```\n私は日本語を勉強します。\nI study Japanese.\n```\n\n```\n彼女は音楽を聞きます。\nShe listens to music.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Polite vs. plain form\n\n| Context | Polite | Plain |\n|---------|--------|-------|\n| Work, strangers | `食べます` ✅ | `食べる` ❌ |\n| Close friends | Both fine | `食べる` ✅ |\n\n---\n\n### Common mistakes\n\n- ❌ Reading `来ます` as `くます` — it's `きます`\n- ❌ Misidentifying verb groups (some る-ending verbs are Group 1!)\n- ✅ Memorize `する → します` and `くる → 来ます` as standalone exceptions\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Pro tip\n\nWhenever you hear `～ます` at the end of a verb, you're in polite territory. The more ます forms you use, the more formal and respectful your speech sounds."
