                    "short_description": "Please don't do",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～ないでください — \"Please don't\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～ないでください` is a **polite negative request** — asking someone to refrain from doing something. You'll see it on signs, in instructions, and hear it in polite conversation.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[dictionary form\n] → negative (ない) + でください\n食べる → 食べない → 食べないでください (please don't eat)\n撮る → 撮らない → 撮らないでください (please don't take photos)\n入る → 入らない → 入らないでください (please don't enter)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\nここで写真を撮らないでください。\nPlease don't take photos here.\n```\n\n```\n廊下を走らないでください。\nPlease don't run in the hallway.\n```\n\n```\nタバコを吸わないでください。\nPlease don't smoke.\n```\n\n```\n遅刻しないでください。\nPlease don't be late.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Politeness scale for prohibitions\n\n| Level | Form | Context |\n|-------|------|---------|\n| Very polite | `～ないようにしてください` | Official notices |\n| Polite | `～ないでください` | Standard |\n| Casual | `～ないで` | With friends |\n| Hard prohibition | `～てはいけません` | Rules/regulations |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Tip\n\nJapanese signs and public notices use `～ないでください` constantly. Recognizing this form means you'll always know what's off-limits."
