                    "md_description": "## Form ～なくてもいいです — \"Don't have to\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～なくてもいいです` expresses **lack of obligation** — \"you don't have to,\"\"it's okay not to.\" It's the opposite of `～なければなりません`.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[dictionary form\n] → ない-form → drop い + くてもいいです\n食べる → 食べなくてもいいです (don't have to eat)\n行く → 行かなくてもいいです (don't have to go)\nする → しなくてもいいです (don't have to do)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n今日は学校に行かなくてもいいです。\nYou don't have to go to school today.\n```\n\n```\n全部食べなくてもいいですよ。\nYou don't have to eat everything.\n```\n\n```\nスーツを着なくてもいいです。\nYou don't have to wear a suit.\n```\n\n```\n急がなくてもいいです。\nThere's no need to rush.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Obligation comparison\n\n| Form | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| `行かなければなりません` | Must go |\n| `行かなくてもいいです` | Don't have to go |\n| `行ってはいけません` | Must not go (prohibition) |\n\n---\n\n### Casual variants\n\n```\n行かなくていい (more neutral)\n行かなくていいよ (with friends)\n```\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Tip\n\nAdding `よ` at the end (`行かなくてもいいですよ`) makes it reassuring and friendly — like saying \"Don't worry about it!\"."
