                    "title": "Form ～たら",
                    "short_description": "If / When (conditional form)",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～たら — \"If/When\" Conditional\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～たら` is the most **versatile conditional form** in Japanese, expressing \"if\" or \"when.\" It works for real conditions, hypotheticals, and temporal sequences alike.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[ta-form\n] + ら\n食べた → 食べたら (if/when you eat)\n行った → 行ったら (if/when you go)\nした → したら (if/when you do)\n来た → 来たら (if/when you come)\n```\n\n**For adjectives:**\n```\n高かった → 高かったら (if it's expensive)\n静かだった → 静かだったら (if it's quiet)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n家に帰ったら、電話してください。\nWhen you get home, please call me.\n```\n\n```\n雨が降ったら、傘を持っていきます。\nIf it rains, I'll bring an umbrella.\n```\n\n```\nお金があったら、旅行したいです。\nIf I had money, I'd want to travel.\n```\n\n```\n春になったら、花見をしましょう。\nWhen spring comes, let's go flower viewing.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Conditional comparison\n\n| Form | Nuance |\n|------|--------|\n| `～たら` | Universal — after condition is met |\n| `～ば` | Logical condition (if A then B) |\n| `～と` | Automatic result |\n| `～なら` | \"If that's the case, then...\" |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Beginner tip\n\n`～たら` is the safest conditional to reach for first — it works in almost any context. Master it before moving on to the others."
