                    "short_description": "If (conditional form)",
                    "md_description": "## Conditional Form ～ば — \"If\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～ば` is a **logical conditional** — \"if A, then B.\" It's commonly used for hypotheticals, advice, proverbs, and general truths.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n**Group 1 verbs:** change u-row to e-row + ば\n```\n飲む → 飲めば (if you drink)\n書く → 書けば (if you write)\n話す → 話せば (if you speak)\n```\n\n**Group 2 verbs:** drop る + れば\n```\n食べる → 食べれば (if you eat)\n見る → 見れば (if you see)\n```\n\n**Group 3:**\n```\nする → すれば\n来る → 来れば\n```\n\n**I-adjectives:** drop い + ければ\n```\n高い → 高ければ (if it's expensive)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n練習すれば、上手になります。\nIf you practice, you'll get better.\n```\n\n```\n早く起きれば、間に合います。\nIf you wake up early, you'll make it.\n```\n\n```\nお金があれば、旅行します。\nIf I have money, I travel.\n```\n\n```\n薬を飲めば、治ります。\nIf you take the medicine, you'll recover.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Limitation\n\n`～ば` doesn't work well when the main clause contains a command, request, or the action of another person. In those cases, use `～たら` instead.\n\n---\n\n### Useful fixed expressions\n\n- `よければ` — if you'd like / if you don't mind\n- `～ばよかった` — I should have... (regret)\n- `どうすれば` — what should I do to...?"
