                    "title": "Volitional form ～よう",
                    "short_description": "Let's do (plain form)",
                    "md_description": "## Volitional Form ～よう — \"Let's\" (Plain Form)\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～よう` is the **plain volitional form** — the casual equivalent of `～ましょう`. Use it with friends, in inner monologue, or when expressing intent.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n**Group 1:** change u-row to o-row + う\n```\n飲む → 飲もう (let's drink)\n書く → 書こう (let's write)\n行く → 行こう (let's go)\n```\n\n**Group 2:** drop る + よう\n```\n食べる → 食べよう (let's eat)\n見る → 見よう (let's watch)\n```\n\n**Group 3:**\n```\nする → しよう (let's do)\n来る → 来よう (let's come)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\nさあ、行こう！\nLet's go!\n```\n\n```\n今夜は外で食べよう。\nLet's eat out tonight.\n```\n\n```\n明日から頑張ろう！\nLet's give it our best from tomorrow!\n```\n\n```\n一緒に映画を見よう。\nLet's watch a movie together.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Extended use: ～ようとする\n\n`～よう` + `とする` = \"try to do / be about to do\":\n```\n起きようとしたが、眠かった。\nI tried to get up, but I was sleepy.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Form | Register |\n|------|---------|\n| `食べましょう` | Polite |\n| `食べよう` | Plain/casual |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Tip\n\nUse `～よう` with friends and in inner speech (`よし、やろう！` = \"Alright, let's do this!\"). It sounds more natural than `～ましょう` in casual contexts."
