                    "title": "Potential form",
                    "short_description": "Can do",
                    "md_description": "## Potential Form — \"Can do\"\n\n### What is it?\n\nThe **potential form** expresses **ability or possibility** — \"can,\"\"be able to,\"\"manage to.\"\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n**Group 1:** u-row → e-row + る\n```\n飲む → 飲める (can drink)\n書く → 書ける (can write)\n話す → 話せる (can speak)\n```\n\n**Group 2:** drop る + られる\n```\n食べる → 食べられる (can eat)\n見る → 見られる (can see)\n起きる → 起きられる (can wake up)\n```\n\n> 💡 In casual speech, Group 2 often drops ら:\n> `食べられる` → `食べれる` (colloquial — called ら抜き言葉)\n\n**Group 3:**\n```\nする → できる\n来る → 来られる (casual: 来れる)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n日本語が話せます。\nI can speak Japanese.\n```\n\n```\nこの漢字が読めません。\nI can't read this kanji.\n```\n\n```\n明日、来られますか。\nCan you come tomorrow?\n```\n\n```\n辛い食べ物が食べられます。\nI can eat spicy food.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Object particle: が or を?\n\nWith potential forms, the object typically takes **が**, though **を** is also acceptable:\n```\n日本語が話せる。(more common)\n日本語を話せる。(also correct)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Comparison with ～ことができる\n\n| Form | Style |\n|------|-------|\n| `話せます` | Conversational |\n| `話すことができます` | Formal/written |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Tip\n\n`できる` (from する) also works independently as \"can\" or \"be able to\":\n```\nそれができます。(I can do that.)\n```"
