                    "title": "Passive form",
                    "short_description": "Was done (passive)",
                    "md_description": "## Passive Form — Passive Voice\n\n### What is it?\n\nThe **passive form** expresses that **the subject is receiving an action**. Japanese passive also commonly expresses that the subject was **negatively affected** by an action — the \"suffering passive\" (迷惑の受け身).\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n**Group 1:** u-row → a-row + れる\n```\n飲む → 飲まれる (be drunk)\n書く → 書かれる (be written)\n話す → 話される (be spoken)\n```\n\n**Group 2:** drop る + られる\n```\n食べる → 食べられる (be eaten)\n見る → 見られる (be seen)\n```\n\n**Group 3:**\n```\nする → される (be done)\n来る → 来られる (have someone come)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Sentence structure\n\n```\n[Subject (が/は)\n] + [agent (に)\n] + [passive verb\n]\n私は先生に褒められました。\nI was praised by my teacher.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n**Neutral passive:**\n```\nこの小説は夏目漱石によって書かれました。\nThis novel was written by Natsume Soseki.\n```\n\n**Suffering passive (negative nuance):**\n```\n雨に降られました。\nI got caught in the rain. (unwanted)\n```\n\n```\n電車の中で足を踏まれました。\nSomeone stepped on my foot in the train.\n```\n\n```\n財布を盗まれました。\nMy wallet was stolen.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Unique Japanese feature\n\nEven **intransitive verbs** can appear in passive to express that something inconvenient happened:\n```\n友達に来られて、困りました。\nA friend came over and it put me in a difficult spot.\n```\n\n---\n\n### ⚠️ Watch out\n\nGroup 2 passive (`食べられる`) looks identical to the potential form. Context tells them apart."
