                    "title": "Imperative form",
                    "short_description": "Do! (command)",
                    "md_description": "## Imperative Form — Direct Commands\n\n### What is it?\n\nThe **imperative form** is the most blunt command form in Japanese. It's used in **military orders, masculine rough speech, manga/anime, sports cheers**. In everyday polite conversation, it's avoided entirely.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n**Group 1:** u-row → e-row\n```\n飲む → 飲め (drink!)\n書く → 書け (write!)\n話す → 話せ (speak!)\n```\n\n**Group 2:** drop る + ろ (or よ)\n```\n食べる → 食べろ / 食べよ (eat!)\n見る → 見ろ / 見よ (watch!)\n```\n\n**Group 3:**\n```\nする → しろ / せよ (do!)\n来る → 来い (come!)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n早く起きろ！\nGet up already!\n```\n\n```\n静かにしろ！\nShut up! / Be quiet!\n```\n\n```\n頑張れ！\nGo for it! / Don't give up!\n```\n\n```\n来い！\nCome here!\n```\n\n---\n\n### Negative imperative (prohibition)\n\n```\n[dictionary form\n] + な\n食べるな！ (Don't eat!)\n来るな！ (Don't come!)\n```\n\n---\n\n### When NOT to use it\n\n- ❌ With strangers (extremely rude)\n- ❌ In the workplace\n- ✅ Sports cheers: `頑張れ！`\n- ✅ Fiction, manga, anime\n\n---\n\n### 💡 For softer commands\n\nUse `～てください` or `～てくれ` (blunt but not a command):\n```\nちょっと待ってくれ。(Wait a sec.)\n```"
