                    "short_description": "Looks like it will happen",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～そう (verb) — \"Looks like it's about to happen\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～そう` after a verb expresses that **something is about to happen** based on visible evidence — an imminent event you can see coming.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[ます-stem\n] + そう (+ です for politeness)\n降ります → 降りそうです (looks like rain is coming)\n泣きます → 泣きそうです (looks like they'll cry)\n倒れます → 倒れそうです (looks like they'll fall)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n空が暗くなってきた。雨が降りそうです。\nThe sky has gotten dark. It looks like it's going to rain.\n```\n\n```\n彼女は泣きそうな顔をしています。\nShe looks like she's about to cry.\n```\n\n```\nこのケーキ、おいしそう！\nThis cake looks delicious!\n```\n\n```\n子供が転びそうです。\nThe child looks like they're about to fall.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Key distinction: ～そう (appearance) vs. ～そうです (hearsay)\n\n| Form | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| `雨が降りそうです` | It looks like rain (I can see the clouds) |\n| `雨が降るそうです` | I heard it's going to rain (someone told me) |\n\n---\n\n### ⚠️ Irregular forms\n\n```\nよさそう (from いい — looks good) ← NOT いそう!\nなさそう (from ない — doesn't seem to exist) ← NOT なそう!\n```\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Key formula\n\n**ます-stem + そう** = your personal visual impression. It's what you see, not what you heard."
