                "English": {
                    "title": "Form ～ようだ",
                    "short_description": "Seems like / As if",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～ようだ — \"It seems like\" / \"It appears that\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～ようだ` expresses a **reasoned conclusion** based on available evidence — \"it seems like,\"\"apparently,\"\"it appears that.\" More analytical than `～そう`.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n| Type | Rule | Example |\n|------|------|---------|\n| Verb (plain form) | + ようだ | `行くようだ` |\n| I-adjective | + ようだ | `高いようだ` |\n| Na-adjective | + なようだ | `静かなようだ` |\n| Noun | + のようだ | `先生のようだ` |\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\n彼は疲れているようだ。\nHe seems to be tired.\n```\n\n```\n試験は難しかったようです。\nThe exam seems to have been difficult.\n```\n\n```\n外は雨のようですね。\nIt sounds like it's raining outside.\n```\n\n```\n彼女は学生のようです。\nShe seems to be a student.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Comparative use: ～ように\n\n`のように` = \"like,\"\"similar to\":\n```\n彼は魚のように泳ぎます。\nHe swims like a fish.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Three related forms compared\n\n| Form | Basis | Nuance |\n|------|-------|--------|\n| `～そうだ` | Visual impression | \"I can see it\" |\n| `～ようだ` | Reasoned inference | \"Based on evidence...\" |\n| `～らしい` | Hearsay/typicality | \"I heard / typical of\" |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Tip\n\nIn polite speech, `ようだ` becomes `ようです`. The softer `ような気がする` adds even more personal tentativeness."
