                    "short_description": "Hard to do",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～にくい — \"Hard to do\" / \"Difficult to do\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～にくい` expresses that an action is **naturally difficult or inconvenient** — usually due to the nature of the thing, not the person's lack of skill.\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[ます-stem\n] + にくい\n書きます → 書きにくい (hard to write with)\n読みます → 読みにくい (hard to read)\n使います → 使いにくい (inconvenient to use)\n食べます → 食べにくい (hard to eat)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\nこのペンは書きにくいです。\nThis pen is hard to write with.\n```\n\n```\nあの先生の話は聞きにくいです。\nThat teacher is hard to listen to (e.g., speaks quietly).\n```\n\n```\nこの道は歩きにくいです。\nThis road is difficult to walk on.\n```\n\n```\n硬い肉は食べにくいです。\nTough meat is hard to chew.\n```\n\n---\n\n### ～にくい conjugates like an i-adjective\n\n```\n書きにくいです (hard)\n書きにくくないです (not hard)\n書きにくかったです (was hard)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Contrast: ～にくい vs. ～やすい\n\n| Form | Meaning |\n|------|---------|\n| `書きにくい` | Hard to write |\n| `書きやすい` | Easy to write |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Key distinction\n\n`～にくい` is about **the inherent difficulty** of the object/situation — not about your personal inability to do something."
