                    "md_description": "## Form ～てしまう — \"Completely done\" / \"Ended up doing\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～てしまう` carries two main nuances:\n1. **Completion** — \"finished doing,\"\"it's all done\"\n2. **Regret/unintended result** — \"accidentally did,\"\"ended up doing (and now I feel bad)\"\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[て-form\n] + しまう\n食べる → 食べてしまう (ate it all / accidentally ate it)\n忘れる → 忘れてしまう (completely forgot / unfortunately forgot)\n壊す → 壊してしまう (broke it completely)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples: Completion\n\n```\n宿題をしてしまいました。\nI've already finished my homework.\n```\n\n```\nその本を読んでしまいました。\nI've already read the whole book.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples: Regret\n\n```\n財布を忘れてしまいました。\nI accidentally left my wallet behind.\n```\n\n```\n大切なデータを消してしまいました。\nI accidentally deleted important data.\n```\n\n```\nケーキを全部食べてしまった。\nI went and ate all the cake (oops).\n```\n\n---\n\n### Casual contractions: ～ちゃう / ～じゃう\n\n```\n食べてしまう → 食べちゃう\n飲んでしまう → 飲んじゃう\n```\n\n---\n\n### 💡 How to tell the meanings apart?\n\n- Neutral context → **completion**\n- Undesirable result → **regret**\n- Often both overlap — \"it's done and there's no going back\" — which is precisely the nuance the form carries."
