                    "short_description": "Want someone to do",
                    "md_description": "## Form ～てほしい — \"Want someone to do\"\n\n### What is it?\n\n`～てほしい` expresses **wanting another person to do something** — \"I want you to...,\"\"I'd like you to...\"\n\n---\n\n### Formation\n\n```\n[て-form\n] + ほしい\n来る → 来てほしい (want you to come)\n手伝う → 手伝ってほしい (want you to help)\n止める → 止めてほしい (want you to stop)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Examples\n\n```\nもっと練習してほしいです。\nI want you to practice more.\n```\n\n```\n早く来てほしいです。\nI want you to come early.\n```\n\n```\nタバコをやめてほしいです。\nI want you to quit smoking.\n```\n\n```\n正直に話してほしかったです。\nI wished you had been honest with me.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Sentence structure\n\n```\n[person\n] に + [て-form\n] + ほしい\n友達に来てほしい。(I want my friend to come.)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Negative forms\n\n```\n行ってほしくないです。(I don't want you to go.)\n行かないでほしいです。(I want you to not go.)\n```\n\n---\n\n### ⚠️ Politeness note\n\n`～てほしい` can sound pressuring. In formal contexts, opt for `～ていただけますか` instead."
